injuries.longComment: Ward opened the week with a DNP, though he's been working through multiple injuries to start the season, so his limited session Thursday is likely a result of load-management. He should avoid an injury designation heading into Sunday's road game against the Lions with a full practice Friday. Ward has eight tackles (six solo) and two pass defenses through the first three games of the regular season.

injuries.longComment: The third game of Graham's NFL career was by far his best. In addition to the half sack, he recorded three pressures, including one that set up a teammate's sack. Pro Football Focus gave him a pass-rush grade of 76.9 for the game after the rookie averaged 53.7 over his first two weeks. Graham lines up on the interior with Maliek Collins, who grades out highest among defensive tackles at 91.5 through three games.
injuries.shortComment: Graham had three tackles and half a sack in a 13-10 win over the Packers in Week 3.

injuries.longComment: In a corresponding transaction, the Browns signed offensive tackle Thayer Munford on Wednesday. Jones sustained an ugly knee injury in the first quarter of Week 3 action versus the Packers when cornerback Javon Bullard (concussion) made a low hit on him, and now he'll have to spend the rest of the season on Cleveland's injured reserve list. For the time being, veteran Cornelius Lucas projects to start at left tackle.

injuries.longComment: Bush finished third on the Browns in total tackles behind Carson Schwesinger and Grant Delpit (nine each). Bush has logged at least seven tackles in each of the first three games of the regular season and is on pace to surpass his total across 16 games in 2024 (76).

injuries.longComment: Garrett wreaked havoc on the Packers' offensive line, and he combined with Adin Huntington on an eight-yard sack on Jordan Love late in the second quarter, which led to Green Bay punting on the next play. Garrett is up to 4.0 sacks through three games this season, which is tied with Byron Young and Brian Burns for second most in the NFL behind Rashan Gary (4.5).
injuries.shortComment: Garrett logged six tackles (two solo), including 0.5 sacks, during the Browns' 13-10 win over the Packers on Sunday.

injuries.longComment: There were a few heroes on defense and special teams, but Szmyt gets the headliner. His 55-yard field goal with no time left on the clock won the game for the Browns. It was the second straight week of redemption for the kicker, who missed two kicks in the season-opening, one-point loss to the Bengals.
injuries.shortComment: Szmyt converted both of his field-goal attempts and lone extra-point kick in Sunday's 13-10 win over the Packers.

injuries.longComment: Thrash, a fifth-round draft pick in 2024, was hoping to make a leap in his second season, but he's no better than fourth on the depth chart. He opened the season competing with Isaiah Bond as the No. 3, but Thrash played just 12 snaps Sunday compared to Bond's 43. Thrash has four catches for 18 yards through three weeks.

injuries.longComment: Bond made his first start of the season and was given 43 snaps, nearly as many he had over the first two games. He's gone from 21 snaps in Week 1 to 28 in Week 2 before prior to a big jump in usage Sunday. Bond has emerged as the Browns'  No. 3 wideout, which might normally hold value but not necessarily on an offense that has managed to score only 15 points per game.

injuries.longComment: Tanin was tied for third in receptions and targets on the Browns for the afternoon while also garnering that slotting in receiving yards. It was Fannin's quietest performance yet in his brief NFL career, but the rookie third-round pick is clearly a key component of the passing attack and could enjoy a bigger role in a Week 4 road matchup against the Lions for which Cleveland figures to have to remain aggressive on offense.

injuries.longComment: Sampson was on the field for just five offensive snaps and went untargeted for the first time in three weeks. He had eight targets in Week 1 followed by a touchdown catch last week, but it looks like Jerome Ford has emerged as the primary target out of the backfield. In addition to the diminished targets, Sampson's overall usage has taken a hit, dropping from 33 snaps in Week 1 to 17 in Week 2 and now five. That drop coincides with the availability of Quinshon Judkins.
injuries.shortComment: Sampson had one carry for two yards in Sunday's 13-10 win over the Packers in Week 3.

injuries.longComment: Ford didn't get a carry for the first time in three weeks, but he has emerged as a primary target out of the backfield. He actually caught a fifth pass, but the play was negated by a holding penalty. Ford has 10 official targets over the last two weeks and 11 for the season. That's tied with Dylan Sampson for the lead among Cleveland's running backs, but Sampson went untargeted Sunday and has just three over the last two weeks. Ford was not used in the return game after returning six kicks in Week 2.
injuries.shortComment: Ford caught all four targets for 10 yards in Sunday's 13-10 win over Green Bay in Week 3.
